  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "One can obtain individual web documents from the WARC chunks directly from the Common Crawl servers, as we demonstrated in our recent paper [14]: requests.get( f'https://data.commoncrawl.org/{warc_file}' headers={ 'Range': f'bytes={offset}-{offset+length-1}' })In the code snippet above, we use requests Python library 12 to retrieve an individual scraped web document from a CC warc_file using the Range HTTP header, only reading the bytes of the relevant web document by knowing its location within the warc_file, including the offset from the start of the warc_file, and the web document's length in bytes.In this work, we will focus on three CC releases spanning the last five years, CC-MAIN-{2019-09,2021-39,2024-10}.",
    "What constitutes geospatialThe vast majority of the files found in CC are standard web pages, such as HTML and XML pages.",
    "In fact, the share of CC files that are exclusively geospatial, such as.geojson or.kml, is only roughly 0.003-0.004%.",
    "Table 1 shows all geospatial MIME types that we were able to identify from the index of the three studied CC releases.",
    "Therefore, our main goal is to estimate the prevalence of geospatial content in predominantly non-geospatial files.According to the ISO's definition of geographic data (which is essentially the same as geospatial data), it must contain 'implicit or explicit reference to a location relative to the Earth' [15]."
  ],
